### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90. If the number of Doberman puppies is 20, how many Schnauzers are there?<n>Output: Three times the number of Doberman puppies is 3*20=<<3*20=60>>60<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies is 60-5=<<60-5=55>>55<n>Let's say the number of Schnauzers is s.<n>The difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is s-20<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90, meaning 55+s-20=90.<n>The number of Schnauzers which is s+55-20=90<n>This evaluates to s+35=90<n>There are s=<<55=55>>55 Schnauzers<n>So the final answer is 55<n><n>Input: Dr. Banks had 330 toothbrushes to give away to his patients. He gave away 53 toothbrushes in January. He gave away 67 toothbrushes in February. In March he gave away 46 toothbrushes. In April and May, he gave away the remaining toothbrushes, half each month.  How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Output: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>So the final answer is 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. On Tuesday, she picks half as many seashells as she did on Monday. If she can sell each seashell for $1.20, how much money can she make if she sells all of her seashells?<n>Output: On Tuesday, Sally picks 30 / 2 = <<30/2=15>>15 seashells<n>In total, Sally picks 30 + 15 = <<30+15=45>>45 seashells<n>The total amount of money Sally can make is 45 * $1.20 = $<<45*1.2=54>>54<n>So the final answer is 54<n><n>Input: Jordan and Perry took a boat out to the lake to go fishing on a Monday morning. Jordan caught 4 fish and Perry caught double what Jordan caught. On the way back to shore, the boat tipped over and they lost one-fourth of their total catch. How many fish remain?<n>Output: Since Perry caught double what Jordan caught, Perry caught 2 * 4 = <<2*4=8>>8 fish.<n>Altogether, they caught 8 + 4 = <<8+4=12>>12 fish.<n>On the way back to the shore, they lost 12 * 1/4 = <<12*1/4=3>>3 fish.<n>They have 12 - 3 = <<12-3=9>>9 fish remaining.<n>So the final answer is 9<n><n>Input:He got a job dancing and waving an advertisement, he got to be outside instead of stuck inside the what? Choices:  A: advertisement B: magazine C: store D: web page E: bus<n>Output:		He didn't get a job waving a flier for a bus, so he got to be outside.<n><n>Input: A pizza pie has 6 slices, I ate 2 of those slices (32% of the pizza), why couldn't I eat any more (40%), because there was only one slice (0.167) left?<n>Output: In total, there are 6 slices - 2 slices, therefore there are 4 slices left - 2 slices.<n>This evaluates to 0.2 + 2 - 2 = <<0.2+2-2=0>>0 slices left, so the final answer is 0<n><n>Input: Sasha and the three bears are hiking a mountain. Sasha comes across a bear. To lose the bear, Sasha needs to go at least twice the rate the bear goes. Sasha is walking at a pace of 1 mile per hour and the bears are walking at 2 miles per hour. What needs to happen for Sasha to lose the bear?<n>Output: Sasha must walk 2 miles per hour in order to lose the bear.<n>Sasha must walk 2 * (2 * 1) = <<2*2*1=4>>4 miles per hour to lose the bear.

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90. If the number of Doberman puppies is 20, how many Schnauzers are there?<n>Output: Three times the number of Doberman puppies is 3*20=<<3*20=60>>60<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies is 60-5=<<60-5=55>>55<n>Let's say the number of Schnauzers is s.<n>The difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is s-20<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90, meaning 55+s-20=90.<n>The number of Schnauzers which is s+55-20=90<n>This evaluates to s+35=90<n>There are s=<<55=55>>55 Schnauzers<n>So the final answer is 55<n><n>Input: Dr. Banks had 330 toothbrushes to give away to his patients. He gave away 53 toothbrushes in January. He gave away 67 toothbrushes in February. In March he gave away 46 toothbrushes. In April and May, he gave away the remaining toothbrushes, half each month.  How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Output: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>So the final answer is 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. On Tuesday, she picks half as many seashells as she did on Monday. If she can sell each seashell for $1.20, how much money can she make if she sells all of her seashells?<n>Output: On Tuesday, Sally picks 30 / 2 = <<30/2=15>>15 seashells<n>In total, Sally picks 30 + 15 = <<30+15=45>>45 seashells<n>The total amount of money Sally can make is 45 * $1.20 = $<<45*1.2=54>>54<n>So the final answer is 54<n><n>Input: Jordan and Perry took a boat out to the lake to go fishing on a Monday morning. Jordan caught 4 fish and Perry caught double what Jordan caught. On the way back to shore, the boat tipped over and they lost one-fourth of their total catch. How many fish remain?<n>Output: Since Perry caught double what Jordan caught, Perry caught 2 * 4 = <<2*4=8>>8 fish.<n>Altogether, they caught 8 + 4 = <<8+4=12>>12 fish.<n>On the way back to the shore, they lost 12 * 1/4 = <<12*1/4=3>>3 fish.<n>They have 12 - 3 = <<12-3=9>>9 fish remaining.<n>So the final answer is 9<n><n>Input:One might find theirs open, with the letters that had been delivered stolen. ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90. If the number of Doberman puppies is 20, how many Schnauzers are there?<n>Output: Three times the number of Doberman puppies is 3*20=<<3*20=60>>60<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies is 60-5=<<60-5=55>>55<n>Let's say the number of Schnauzers is s.<n>The difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is s-20<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90, meaning 55+s-20=90.<n>The number of Schnauzers which is s+55-20=90<n>This evaluates to s+35=90<n>There are s=<<55=55>>55 Schnauzers<n>So the final answer is 55<n><n>Input: Dr. Banks had 330 toothbrushes to give away to his patients. He gave away 53 toothbrushes in January. He gave away 67 toothbrushes in February. In March he gave away 46 toothbrushes. In April and May, he gave away the remaining toothbrushes, half each month.  How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Output: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>So the final answer is 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. On Tuesday, she picks half as many seashells as she did on Monday. If she can sell each seashell for $1.20, how much money can she make if she sells all of her seashells?<n>Output: On Tuesday, Sally picks 30 / 2 = <<30/2=15>>15 seashells<n>In total, Sally picks 30 + 15 = <<30+15=45>>45 seashells<n>The total amount of money Sally can make is 45 * $1.20 = $<<45*1.2=54>>54<n>So the final answer is 54<n><n>Input: Jordan and Perry took a boat out to the lake to go fishing on a Monday morning. Jordan caught 4 fish and Perry caught double what Jordan caught. On the way back to shore, the boat tipped over and they lost one-fourth of their total catch. How many fish remain?<n>Output: Since Perry caught double what Jordan caught, Perry caught 2 * 4 = <<2*4=8>>8 fish.<n>Altogether, they caught 8 + 4 = <<8+4=12>>12 fish.<n>On the way back to the shore, they lost 12 * 1/4 = <<12*1/4=3>>3 fish.<n>They have 12 - 3 = <<12-3=9>>9 fish remaining.<n>So the final answer is 9<n><n>Input:Where are a lot of offices in New York? Choices:  A: school building B: skyscraper C: business D: grocery store. E: work<n>Output:		If I ask you why A is the answer to this question, you will probably answer “because A is a school building”. If I ask you why B is the answer to this problem, you will probably answer”because B is a skyscraper”. Similarly, if I ask you why C is the answer to this trivia question, you will probably say”because C is a business”. If I ask you the answer to this question and you answer D is because it’s a grocery store, I’ll probably laugh at you. If I ask you the question above and you answer E, I’ll probably ask “Where is my office?” and you’ll probably say “you went there but you didn’t bring me anything!”. Since every choice but E is a building, you’ll answer one of the buildings except my office. The number of choices where every choice is a building is three, which is the same as the number of choices E is not a building. Therefore, E is the answer to this math trivia.<n><n>Input: You have an equation of a line. The equation is y = ax + b where a is a constant greater than one. You also have two points on the line, (0, c) and (x, f(x)). How do you graph the line?<n>Output: y is the slope of the line (the derivative) and a is the coefficient of y. The equation can be written y = x (a * y) + (b * x)<n>Flip the equation over and put the x and y values:<n>x = (a * y) / (a * y)<n>x = y / (a * y). y = x / (a * x)<n>If you plug in the values at (0, c) (a * 0) you get 0, and plug in the values at f(x) x you get f(x)<n>The graph of y = a * x + b<n><n><n>

The number of people who eat no ice cream is thrice the sum of the people who eat one ice cream and who eat no ice creams. The number of people with dog owned are equal to twice the number of people who like vanilla ice cream. How many people like vanilla ice creams?<n>Output: Let's assume that the total number of people is N and the no. of people with a dog is d.<n>The number of dogs owned by dogs who eat ice cream is 2N-2N+1d, where -1d is the number of dogs without owners.<n>The number of people who eat both dogs and ice cream is 3N-3N-2d.<n>Hence, The number of dogs + no. of dogs who eat ice creams - 3N + no. of ice cream eaters- total number of dogs = 2N-2d<n>N * d - 2N + 3N - n - 3N = 2D/3<n>(N-2)*d = 2D/6<n>or D = 12 * (N-2)/(2)<n>D = <<12*(N-2)/2>>D = 6*(N-2)/4<n>or d = <<6*(N-2)>>d = 3*(N-2) - 2<n>Therefore, the final answer is N-2.<n>
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90. If the number of Doberman puppies is 20, how many Schnauzers are there?<n>Output: Three times the number of Doberman puppies is 3*20=<<3*20=60>>60<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies is 60-5=<<60-5=55>>55<n>Let's say the number of Schnauzers is s.<n>The difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is s-20<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90, meaning 55+s-20=90.<n>The number of Schnauzers which is s+55-20=90<n>This evaluates to s+35=90<n>There are s=<<55=55>>55 Schnauzers<n>So the final answer is 55<n><n>Input: Dr. Banks had 330 toothbrushes to give away to his patients. He gave away 53 toothbrushes in January. He gave away 67 toothbrushes in February. In March he gave away 46 toothbrushes. In April and May, he gave away the remaining toothbrushes, half each month.  How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Output: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>So the final answer is 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. On Tuesday, she picks half as many seashells as she did on Monday. If she can sell each seashell for $1.20, how much money can she make if she sells all of her seashells?<n>Output: On Tuesday, Sally picks 30 / 2 = <<30/2=15>>15 seashells<n>In total, Sally picks 30 + 15 = <<30+15=45>>45 seashells<n>The total amount of money Sally can make is 45 * $1.20 = $<<45*1.2=54>>54<n>So the final answer is 54<n><n>Input: Jordan and Perry took a boat out to the lake to go fishing on a Monday morning. Jordan caught 4 fish and Perry caught double what Jordan caught. On the way back to shore, the boat tipped over and they lost one-fourth of their total catch. How many fish remain?<n>Output: Since Perry caught double what Jordan caught, Perry caught 2 * 4 = <<2*4=8>>8 fish.<n>Altogether, they caught 8 + 4 = <<8+4=12>>12 fish.<n>On the way back to the shore, they lost 12 * 1/4 = <<12*1/4=3>>3 fish.<n>They have 12 - 3 = <<12-3=9>>9 fish remaining.<n>So the final answer is 9<n><n>Input:James was looking for a place to buy bitcoins.  He searched and found a large menu of what? Choices:  A: advertisement B: news C: bar D: cafe E: internet sites<n>Output:		James was Looking for a place to buy Bitcoins, Choices:   A: Advertisement B: News  C: Bar D: Cafe E: Internet Sites so the final answer is C<n><n>Input:There were 44 students in Tayler's computer science class.  On one Wednesday, three students were absent, and on another Wednesday, six students were absent.  How many of the students were absent on an average day of the week?<n>Output:There were 40 students in Tayler computer science class<n>So Total Students minus 3<n>Students are absent on Wednesday<n>Wednesday minus 1 = 5<n>16 students are absent on average day in class<n>So the final answer  is E<n><n>Input:Cody and his friends had two bags of marshmallows: one was half as heavy as the other. They also had three bags of chocolate candy.  Cody shared out the marshmallows so that there was one bag of chocolate cake for every three bags of marsh-mallows. How many bags of marsh mallows remain?<n>Output:First Cody Shared one of the Bags of chocolate to 3 = One extra bag of chocolate left<n>Total bags of marsh - mallows remaining = <<4 - 1 = 3>>3 bags of marshallows<n>So the final answer Cody has = <<3>>3 bags<n><n>Input:  There were 57 pencils in the backpack  of  a science teacher when she had a bag of pencils stolen  from her 57-pound  backpack  34 pencils were missing when the teacher returned <n>to the classroom   After she wrote down the number of remaining pencils,  the  teacher took away two pencils from the pencil  case How many pencils were remaining in the pencil case?<n>Output:Total pencils in bagg -57  -57<n>Minus Total pencils -34 -34<n>Result left after subtraction of numbers is 23 so the answer is C<n><n># Output<n>Output:<n> <n>Input: 9 -2 5<n>3<n>Input: 2
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90. If the number of Doberman puppies is 20, how many Schnauzers are there?<n>Output: Three times the number of Doberman puppies is 3*20=<<3*20=60>>60<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies is 60-5=<<60-5=55>>55<n>Let's say the number of Schnauzers is s.<n>The difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is s-20<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90, meaning 55+s-20=90.<n>The number of Schnauzers which is s+55-20=90<n>This evaluates to s+35=90<n>There are s=<<55=55>>55 Schnauzers<n>So the final answer is 55<n><n>Input: Dr. Banks had 330 toothbrushes to give away to his patients. He gave away 53 toothbrushes in January. He gave away 67 toothbrushes in February. In March he gave away 46 toothbrushes. In April and May, he gave away the remaining toothbrushes, half each month.  How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Output: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>So the final answer is 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. On Tuesday, she picks half as many seashells as she did on Monday. If she can sell each seashell for $1.20, how much money can she make if she sells all of her seashells?<n>Output: On Tuesday, Sally picks 30 / 2 = <<30/2=15>>15 seashells<n>In total, Sally picks 30 + 15 = <<30+15=45>>45 seashells<n>The total amount of money Sally can make is 45 * $1.20 = $<<45*1.2=54>>54<n>So the final answer is 54<n><n>Input: Jordan and Perry took a boat out to the lake to go fishing on a Monday morning. Jordan caught 4 fish and Perry caught double what Jordan caught. On the way back to shore, the boat tipped over and they lost one-fourth of their total catch. How many fish remain?<n>Output: Since Perry caught double what Jordan caught, Perry caught 2 * 4 = <<2*4=8>>8 fish.<n>Altogether, they caught 8 + 4 = <<8+4=12>>12 fish.<n>On the way back to the shore, they lost 12 * 1/4 = <<12*1/4=3>>3 fish.<n>They have 12 - 3 = <<12-3=9>>9 fish remaining.<n>So the final answer is 9<n><n>Input:Where can you store a small notepad on your person? If she can sell each seashell for $1.20, how much money can she make if she sells all of her seashells?<n>Output: On Tuesday, Sally picks 30 / 2 = <<30/2=15>>15 seashells<n>In total, Sally picks 30 + 15 = <<30+15=45>>45 seashells<n>The total amount of money Sally can make is 45 * $1.20 = $<<45*1.2=54>>54<n>So the final answer is 54<n><n>Input: Jordan and Perry took a boat out to the lake to go fishing on a Monday morning. Jordan caught 4 fish and Perry caught double what Jordan caught. On the way back to shore, the boat tipped over and they lost one-fourth of their total catch. How many fish remain?<n>Output: Since Perry caught double what Jordan caught, Perry caught 2 * 4 = <<2*4=8>>8 fish.<n>Altogether, they caught 8 + 4 = <<8+4=12>>12 fish.<n>On the way back to the shore, they lost 12 * 1/4 = <<12*1/4=3>>3 fish.<n>They have 12 - 3 = <<12-3=9>>9 fish remaining.<n>So the final answer is 9<n><n>Input:He found the blowfish off the coast of the Carolina's, it was where? Choices:  A: rock band B: sea of japan C: sushi restaurant D: fish market E: atlantic ocean<n>Output:		<<b=carolinas>><n><n>Input: A tree has a root with radius r meters. How many roots does the tree have if the tree's radius is 3 meters? Explain your thinking.<n>Output: In order to be able to divide the root by two, it would need a factor two<n>Root has radius r meters, as r2 goes through the square root two it becomes r2-r+2 which after going through factor two will result in r2-r = r-r+2 or just r as per its square<n>So there is atleast 1 root<n><n>Input:A woman bought 5 shirts and sold 2 more than to the same clothing store. How many shirts did she buy? Explain your thinking?<n>Output:Let us say the number of shirts she bought = b<n>Then she sold 2 more than that<n>So total no. of shirts she sold = b+2<n>So the amount of shirts she'll buy = b+2-b = 2<n>So the woman will buy 2 shirts<n><n>Input: How many fish are in a bag of 72 fish, if the ratio of females to males in the bag is 7:6?<n>Output:let x be the no. of fishes<n>Then 72:72:(x+2) =7:6<n>Then x =48(72/7)=48/7 = 7(67/48) = 67/48<n>So x=65<n>Then no. of females=65*7/12=40.8<n>
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90. If the number of Doberman puppies is 20, how many Schnauzers are there?<n>Output: Three times the number of Doberman puppies is 3*20=<<3*20=60>>60<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies is 60-5=<<60-5=55>>55<n>Let's say the number of Schnauzers is s.<n>The difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is s-20<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90, meaning 55+s-20=90.<n>The number of Schnauzers which is s+55-20=90<n>This evaluates to s+35=90<n>There are s=<<55=55>>55 Schnauzers<n>So the final answer is 55<n><n>Input: Dr. Banks had 330 toothbrushes to give away to his patients. He gave away 53 toothbrushes in January. He gave away 67 toothbrushes in February. In March he gave away 46 toothbrushes. In April and May, he gave away the remaining toothbrushes, half each month.  How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Output: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>So the final answer is 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. On Tuesday, she picks half as many seashells as she did on Monday. If she can sell each seashell for $1.20, how much money can she make if she sells all of her seashells?<n>Output: On Tuesday, Sally picks 30 / 2 = <<30/2=15>>15 seashells<n>In total, Sally picks 30 + 15 = <<30+15=45>>45 seashells<n>The total amount of money Sally can make is 45 * $1.20 = $<<45*1.2=54>>54<n>So the final answer is 54<n><n>Input: Jordan and Perry took a boat out to the lake to go fishing on a Monday morning. Jordan caught 4 fish and Perry caught double what Jordan caught. On the way back to shore, the boat tipped over and they lost one-fourth of their total catch. How many fish remain?<n>Output: Since Perry caught double what Jordan caught, Perry caught 2 * 4 = <<2*4=8>>8 fish.<n>Altogether, they caught 8 + 4 = <<8+4=12>>12 fish.<n>On the way back to the shore, they lost 12 * 1/4 = <<12*1/4=3>>3 fish.<n>They have 12 - 3 = <<12-3=9>>9 fish remaining.<n>So the final answer is 9<n><n>Input:What area is likely to contain a large village? Choices:  A: rural area B: big city C: suburbs D: ohio E: countryside<n>Output:		The answer is suburbs<n>Input:How do you feel about living in a house on the countryside? Choice A: I like it! Choice B: Oh no! Choice C: I'm indifferent Choice D: I don't want to own a house Choice E: I don't care, I'd prefer to live in a large city<n>Output:<n>You've chosen Option(E). The remaining choices are:<n>Choice A, Option(D), Option(B), Option(C)<n>As you were deciding among these options, choose from any of the following:<n>Choice A: You don't want to live in a house in the countryside<n>Choice B: You want to avoid the countryside like the plague<n>Choice C: You aren't really concerned<n>Choice D: You think you'd be bored<n>There's 1 remaining option. Which of the following would you prefer not to live in a house?<n><n>Input:Given a matrix in the form of a 2D array, the function should return the column of the given matrix in the order given to the function. Input: [[1,2,3,4], [4,3,2,1]] Output: [1,2,3]<n>Input:Given the order as listed on the board, the function should return a new array of size 5 with the given elements in order. Input: [1,2] [3,4,5] [6,7] Output: [1, 2, 3, 4, 5]<n><n><n>### Answer and Explanation<n>- I didn't understand why the second prompt should return the second column because in the instructions it's stated that you can return a list containing a column. ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90. If the number of Doberman puppies is 20, how many Schnauzers are there?<n>Output: Three times the number of Doberman puppies is 3*20=<<3*20=60>>60<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies is 60-5=<<60-5=55>>55<n>Let's say the number of Schnauzers is s.<n>The difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is s-20<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90, meaning 55+s-20=90.<n>The number of Schnauzers which is s+55-20=90<n>This evaluates to s+35=90<n>There are s=<<55=55>>55 Schnauzers<n>So the final answer is 55<n><n>Input: Dr. Banks had 330 toothbrushes to give away to his patients. He gave away 53 toothbrushes in January. He gave away 67 toothbrushes in February. In March he gave away 46 toothbrushes. In April and May, he gave away the remaining toothbrushes, half each month.  How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Output: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>So the final answer is 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. On Tuesday, she picks half as many seashells as she did on Monday. If she can sell each seashell for $1.20, how much money can she make if she sells all of her seashells?<n>Output: On Tuesday, Sally picks 30 / 2 = <<30/2=15>>15 seashells<n>In total, Sally picks 30 + 15 = <<30+15=45>>45 seashells<n>The total amount of money Sally can make is 45 * $1.20 = $<<45*1.2=54>>54<n>So the final answer is 54<n><n>Input: Jordan and Perry took a boat out to the lake to go fishing on a Monday morning. Jordan caught 4 fish and Perry caught double what Jordan caught. On the way back to shore, the boat tipped over and they lost one-fourth of their total catch. How many fish remain?<n>Output: Since Perry caught double what Jordan caught, Perry caught 2 * 4 = <<2*4=8>>8 fish.<n>Altogether, they caught 8 + 4 = <<8+4=12>>12 fish.<n>On the way back to the shore, they lost 12 * 1/4 = <<12*1/4=3>>3 fish.<n>They have 12 - 3 = <<12-3=9>>9 fish remaining.<n>So the final answer is 9<n><n>Input:Shane was supposed to speak at his fathers funeral. ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90. How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Output: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>So the final answer is 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. On Tuesday, she picks half as many seashells as she did on Monday. Jordan caught 4 fish and Perry caught double what Jordan caught. On the way back to shore, the boat tipped over and they lost one-fourth of their total catch. How many fish remain?<n>Output: Since Perry caught double what Jordan caught, Perry caught 2 * 4 = <<2*4=8>>8 fish.<n>Altogether, they caught 8 + 4 = <<8+4=12>>12 fish.<n>On the way back to the shore, they lost 12 * 1/4 = <<12*1/4=3>>3 fish.<n>They have 12 - 3 = <<12-3=9>>9 fish remaining.<n>So the final answer is 9<n><n>Input:When a monkey is taken away from their home they are often brought to this place where people wear white coats. ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90. If the number of Doberman puppies is 20, how many Schnauzers are there?<n>Output: Three times the number of Doberman puppies is 3*20=<<3*20=60>>60<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies is 60-5=<<60-5=55>>55<n>Let's say the number of Schnauzers is s.<n>The difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is s-20<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90, meaning 55+s-20=90.<n>The number of Schnauzers which is s+55-20=90<n>This evaluates to s+35=90<n>There are s=<<55=55>>55 Schnauzers<n>So the final answer is 55<n><n>Input: Dr. Banks had 330 toothbrushes to give away to his patients. How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Output: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>So the final answer is 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90. If the number of Doberman puppies is 20, how many Schnauzers are there?<n>Output: Three times the number of Doberman puppies is 3*20=<<3*20=60>>60<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies is 60-5=<<60-5=55>>55<n>Let's say the number of Schnauzers is s.<n>The difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is s-20<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90, meaning 55+s-20=90.<n>The number of Schnauzers which is s+55-20=90<n>This evaluates to s+35=90<n>There are s=<<55=55>>55 Schnauzers<n>So the final answer is 55<n><n>Input: Dr. Banks had 330 toothbrushes to give away to his patients. He gave away 53 toothbrushes in January. He gave away 67 toothbrushes in February. In March he gave away 46 toothbrushes. In April and May, he gave away the remaining toothbrushes, half each month.  How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Output: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>So the final answer is 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. On Tuesday, she picks half as many seashells as she did on Monday. If she can sell each seashell for $1.20, how much money can she make if she sells all of her seashells?<n>Output: On Tuesday, Sally picks 30 / 2 = <<30/2=15>>15 seashells<n>In total, Sally picks 30 + 15 = <<30+15=45>>45 seashells<n>The total amount of money Sally can make is 45 * $1.20 = $<<45*1.2=54>>54<n>So the final answer is 54<n><n>Input: Jordan and Perry took a boat out to the lake to go fishing on a Monday morning. How many total triangular piles of objects does he need for his arrangment?<n>Output: There are 4 * 3 = <<4*3=12>>13 piles of 4 objects each.<n>Each pile contains the same number of objects, which is N.<n>Since there are N identical layers we can say that each pile consists out of N objects.<n>There are 4 * N ways of putting the object into 4 triangles.<n>This means that there are 4 * N * N = N^2 = <<4*N*N=64>>64 total ways of putting the objects.<n>So the final of the answer of 64.<n><n>Input: A boy is sitting on 6 blue hula hoops and 4 red hula hoops. If two fish swim twice as fast as the third fish, how long does it take until all of the fish swim the same distance?<n>Output: The fish swim the same number of laps as the distance divided by the time, which makes the time for all three fish to do one lap (and swim one distance) the time taken for the slower fish.<n>So the answer is 3 / 1.5 = <<3/1.5=2>>2<n>This makes the time two tanks for the slower fish and to tank of the middle fish and two-tanks for the faster fish.<n>So the final anwser is 2<n><n>Input: 16 x 26= <<16x26=416>>416<n>

If the number of Doberman puppies is 20, how many Schnauzers are there?<n>Output: Three times the number of Doberman puppies is 3*20=<<3*20=60>>60<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies is 60-5=<<60-5=55>>55<n>Let's say the number of Schnauzers is s.<n>The difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is s-20<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90, meaning 55+s-20=90.<n>The number of Schnauzers which is s+55-20=90<n>This evaluates to s+35=90<n>There are s=<<55=55>>55 Schnauzers<n>So the final answer is 55<n><n>Input: Dr. Banks had 330 toothbrushes to give away to his patients. He gave away 53 toothbrushes in January. He gave away 67 toothbrushes in February. In March he gave away 46 toothbrushes. In April and May, he gave away the remaining toothbrushes, half each month.  How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Output: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>So the final answer is 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. On Tuesday, she picks half as many seashells as she did on Monday. If she can sell each seashell for $1.20, how much money can she make if she sells all of her seashells?<n>Output: On Tuesday, Sally picks 30 / 2 = <<30/2=15>>15 seashells<n>In total, Sally picks 30 + 15 = <<30+15=45>>45 seashells<n>The total amount of money Sally can make is 45 * $1.20 = $<<45*1.2=54>>54<n>So the final answer is 54<n><n>Input: Jordan and Perry took a boat out to the lake to go fishing on a Monday morning. Jordan caught 4 fish and Perry caught double what Jordan caught. On the way back to shore, the boat tipped over and they lost one-fourth of their total catch. How many fish remain?<n>Output: Since Perry caught double what Jordan caught, Perry caught 2 * 4 = <<2*4=8>>8 fish.<n>Altogether, they caught 8 + 4 = <<8+4=12>>12 fish.<n>On the way back to the shore, they lost 12 * 1/4 = <<12*1/4=3>>3 fish.<n>They have 12 - 3 = <<12-3=9>>9 fish remaining.<n>So the final answer is 9<n><n>Input:If you socialize by having trivial conversations it is called what? Choices:  A: make friends B: mingle C: meet people D: small talk E: meet new people<n>Output:		A: make friends - small talk is what you do to meet people<n>B: mingle - but you wouldn't mingle with a purpose<n>C: meet people - you would use small talk in order to meet people<n>D: small talk - it's small, not trivial. It is an intentional way to create a connection with someone you don't know<n>E: meet new people - but you would use small talk with a purpose<n>So A is the correct answer<n>Input: A pond contains 400 fish plus two-fifths the number of fish that are in a river. If a pond fisherman gets 1/10th the total number of fish in the pond and river, how many fewer fish are in the river?<n>Output: Total=400+2/(5*400)=401/5<n>After this, total=1/5*401=401/25<n>So final number of fish in rivers=401/5-401/2= -1/5= <<-1/5=-20%> -20%<n>So the final answer fish in rivers is 20% less than before the fisherman's trip<n><n>Input: How do you subtract fractions? Choices:  a: like regular numbers you line them up and subtract b: add the same denominator like you do regular numbers, then take away the answer like regular numbers c: find the least common denominator and then subtract like regular numbers d: what ever you want to do<n>Output: A: like regular numbers you add the numerators and then take away the answer<n>C: find the least common denomonator and then subtract<n>D: what ever you want <n>So A is the Correct answer<n>

How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Output: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>So the final answer is 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. How many fish remain?<n>Output: Since Perry caught double what Jordan caught, Perry caught 2 * 4 = <<2*4=8>>8 fish.<n>Altogether, they caught 8 + 4 = <<8+4=12>>12 fish.<n>On the way back to the shore, they lost 12 * 1/4 = <<12*1/4=3>>3 fish.<n>They have 12 - 3 = <<12-3=9>>9 fish remaining.<n>So the final answer is 9<n><n>Input:If a person is seeing new things, what do they most often feel? How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Output: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>So the final answer is 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. On Tuesday, she picks half as many seashells as she did on Monday. ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90. If the number of Doberman puppies is 20, how many Schnauzers are there?<n>Output: Three times the number of Doberman puppies is 3*20=<<3*20=60>>60<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies is 60-5=<<60-5=55>>55<n>Let's say the number of Schnauzers is s.<n>The difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is s-20<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90, meaning 55+s-20=90.<n>The number of Schnauzers which is s+55-20=90<n>This evaluates to s+35=90<n>There are s=<<55=55>>55 Schnauzers<n>So the final answer is 55<n><n>Input: Dr. Banks had 330 toothbrushes to give away to his patients. He gave away 53 toothbrushes in January. He gave away 67 toothbrushes in February. In March he gave away 46 toothbrushes. In April and May, he gave away the remaining toothbrushes, half each month.  How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Output: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>So the final answer is 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. On Tuesday, she picks half as many seashells as she did on Monday. If she can sell each seashell for $1.20, how much money can she make if she sells all of her seashells?<n>Output: On Tuesday, Sally picks 30 / 2 = <<30/2=15>>15 seashells<n>In total, Sally picks 30 + 15 = <<30+15=45>>45 seashells<n>The total amount of money Sally can make is 45 * $1.20 = $<<45*1.2=54>>54<n>So the final answer is 54<n><n>Input: Jordan and Perry took a boat out to the lake to go fishing on a Monday morning. Jordan caught 4 fish and Perry caught double what Jordan caught. On the way back to shore, the boat tipped over and they lost one-fourth of their total catch. How many fish remain?<n>Output: Since Perry caught double what Jordan caught, Perry caught 2 * 4 = <<2*4=8>>8 fish.<n>Altogether, they caught 8 + 4 = <<8+4=12>>12 fish.<n>On the way back to the shore, they lost 12 * 1/4 = <<12*1/4=3>>3 fish.<n>They have 12 - 3 = <<12-3=9>>9 fish remaining.<n>So the final answer is 9<n><n>Input:The shark was migrating between continents, where did biologists find it? Choices:  A: fresh water B: gulf of mexico C: open ocean D: television program E: coral reef<n>Output:		The shark was in gulf of mexico<n><n>

If she can sell each seashell for $1.20, how much money can she make if she sells all of her seashells?<n>Output: On Tuesday, Sally picks 30 / 2 = <<30/2=15>>15 seashells<n>In total, Sally picks 30 + 15 = <<30+15=45>>45 seashells<n>The total amount of money Sally can make is 45 * $1.20 = $<<45*1.2=54>>54<n>So the final answer is 54<n><n>Input: Jordan and Perry took a boat out to the lake to go fishing on a Monday morning. Jordan caught 4 fish and Perry caught double what Jordan caught. On the way back to shore, the boat tipped over and they lost one-fourth of their total catch. How many fish remain?<n>Output: Since Perry caught double what Jordan caught, Perry caught 2 * 4 = <<2*4=8>>8 fish.<n>Altogether, they caught 8 + 4 = <<8+4=12>>12 fish.<n>On the way back to the shore, they lost 12 * 1/4 = <<12*1/4=3>>3 fish.<n>They have 12 - 3 = <<12-3=9>>9 fish remaining.<n>So the final answer is 9<n><n>Input:The friends loved competing against one another, it was a good way to work their what? Choices:  A: friendship B: aggression C: defeat D: winning or losing E: sweat<n>Output:		A> B> C> D> E<n>So the final answer in this question is A<n><n>Input: I can have a dog named Toto for $1,500 but a puppy named Snoopy is $500 more. Toto runs about 10 miles a day but Snoopy jogs up to 15 miles each day. You get to choose the two dogs that you can buy if your allowance is $1000. <n>Output: The price to buy Toto is $1500<n>The price to buy Snoopy is $1501+$500 = <<1501+500=2001>>2001<n>By giving you $1000, we have enough money to buy either Toto or Snoopy<n>Snoopy is $1001 > <<1001>Toto so you get to choose Snoopy<n>So the final answer to this question is Snoopy<n><n>Input: Your friend has $2,787.50 to spend. ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90. If the number of Doberman puppies is 20, how many Schnauzers are there?<n>Output: Three times the number of Doberman puppies is 3*20=<<3*20=60>>60<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies is 60-5=<<60-5=55>>55<n>Let's say the number of Schnauzers is s.<n>The difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is s-20<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90, meaning 55+s-20=90.<n>The number of Schnauzers which is s+55-20=90<n>This evaluates to s+35=90<n>There are s=<<55=55>>55 Schnauzers<n>So the final answer is 55<n><n>Input: Dr. Banks had 330 toothbrushes to give away to his patients. How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Output: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>So the final answer is 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. Recall that the characters in a string are called “letters”, and the string itself is a “word”.<n># Note: The above groups are simply examples. Use the groups and operations shown below for all cases. Do not use any other groups or operations. Do not change the groups or operations at any point during this problem.<n>### Input Format<n>```<n>string[string[string[string]]]<letter group>[complement of letter group] letter group [letters added to complement of letter group or characters added to first of letters added to complement of letter grouped if word has a vowel character.][letters and characters added to complement of last two letters of word.[string][string][string]string[string][string][string].<n>```<n>### Output Format<n>```<n>True: the letter group and the complement of the letter group are identical.[string][string][]string[string][]string[].<n>```<n># Analysis<n>```<n>if(all group are same)<n>then<n>return true<n>else<n>return false<n>```<n><n>---<n>## A. How could you simplify the above function so that only one line of code is needed to complete each task?<n>### Solution:We can simplify the function by using for..each and apply each element separately i.e. like we can find the maximum element and min element of the array in one line.<n># if we replace for..each with map like this<n># max={}${(group: group)...} max=[map={}${(group:g) -> if(group == max) return min else return g} max=max..let<n># let<n><n># so basically we are saying that when max is not equal to mim we will replace max and when it is equal, just return max <n># similarly when we will be looking for min<n># min={}${(group: g)...

How many fish remain?<n>Output: Since Perry caught double what Jordan caught, Perry caught 2 * 4 = <<2*4=8>>8 fish.<n>Altogether, they caught 8 + 4 = <<8+4=12>>12 fish.<n>On the way back to the shore, they lost 12 * 1/4 = <<12*1/4=3>>3 fish.<n>They have 12 - 3 = <<12-3=9>>9 fish remaining.<n>So the final answer is 9<n><n>Input:Sam didn't like the people he met while traveling. ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90. If the number of Doberman puppies is 20, how many Schnauzers are there?<n>Output: Three times the number of Doberman puppies is 3*20=<<3*20=60>>60<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies is 60-5=<<60-5=55>>55<n>Let's say the number of Schnauzers is s.<n>The difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is s-20<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90, meaning 55+s-20=90.<n>The number of Schnauzers which is s+55-20=90<n>This evaluates to s+35=90<n>There are s=<<55=55>>55 Schnauzers<n>So the final answer is 55<n><n>Input: Dr. Banks had 330 toothbrushes to give away to his patients. He gave away 53 toothbrushes in January. He gave away 67 toothbrushes in February. In March he gave away 46 toothbrushes. In April and May, he gave away the remaining toothbrushes, half each month.  How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Output: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>So the final answer is 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90. If the number of Doberman puppies is 20, how many Schnauzers are there?<n>Output: Three times the number of Doberman puppies is 3*20=<<3*20=60>>60<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies is 60-5=<<60-5=55>>55<n>Let's say the number of Schnauzers is s.<n>The difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is s-20<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90, meaning 55+s-20=90.<n>The number of Schnauzers which is s+55-20=90<n>This evaluates to s+35=90<n>There are s=<<55=55>>55 Schnauzers<n>So the final answer is 55<n><n>Input: Dr. Banks had 330 toothbrushes to give away to his patients. He gave away 53 toothbrushes in January. He gave away 67 toothbrushes in February. In March he gave away 46 toothbrushes. In April and May, he gave away the remaining toothbrushes, half each month.  How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Output: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>So the final answer is 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. On Tuesday, she picks half as many seashells as she did on Monday. If she can sell each seashell for $1.20, how much money can she make if she sells all of her seashells?<n>Output: On Tuesday, Sally picks 30 / 2 = <<30/2=15>>15 seashells<n>In total, Sally picks 30 + 15 = <<30+15=45>>45 seashells<n>The total amount of money Sally can make is 45 * $1.20 = $<<45*1.2=54>>54<n>So the final answer is 54<n><n>Input: Jordan and Perry took a boat out to the lake to go fishing on a Monday morning. Jordan caught 4 fish and Perry caught double what Jordan caught. On the way back to shore, the boat tipped over and they lost one-fourth of their total catch. How many fish remain?<n>Output: Since Perry caught double what Jordan caught, Perry caught 2 * 4 = <<2*4=8>>8 fish.<n>Altogether, they caught 8 + 4 = <<8+4=12>>12 fish.<n>On the way back to the shore, they lost 12 * 1/4 = <<12*1/4=3>>3 fish.<n>They have 12 - 3 = <<12-3=9>>9 fish remaining.<n>So the final answer is 9<n><n>Input:What is KFC who serves chicken? Choices:  A: fast food restaurant B: plate C: bowl D: freezer E: oven<n>Output:		KFC stands for Kentucky Fried Chicken.<n>Kentucky Fried Chicken serves chicken in a box or in a bowl.  That's why C is the right answer<n><n>Output: KFC serves fried chicken<n>Kentucky Fried chicken <n><n><n><n><n><n>
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90. If the number of Doberman puppies is 20, how many Schnauzers are there?<n>Output: Three times the number of Doberman puppies is 3*20=<<3*20=60>>60<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies is 60-5=<<60-5=55>>55<n>Let's say the number of Schnauzers is s.<n>The difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is s-20<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90, meaning 55+s-20=90.<n>The number of Schnauzers which is s+55-20=90<n>This evaluates to s+35=90<n>There are s=<<55=55>>55 Schnauzers<n>So the final answer is 55<n><n>Input: Dr. Banks had 330 toothbrushes to give away to his patients. He gave away 53 toothbrushes in January. He gave away 67 toothbrushes in February. In March he gave away 46 toothbrushes. In April and May, he gave away the remaining toothbrushes, half each month.  How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Output: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>So the final answer is 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. On Tuesday, she picks half as many seashells as she did on Monday. If she can sell each seashell for $1.20, how much money can she make if she sells all of her seashells?<n>Output: On Tuesday, Sally picks 30 / 2 = <<30/2=15>>15 seashells<n>In total, Sally picks 30 + 15 = <<30+15=45>>45 seashells<n>The total amount of money Sally can make is 45 * $1.20 = $<<45*1.2=54>>54<n>So the final answer is 54<n><n>Input: Jordan and Perry took a boat out to the lake to go fishing on a Monday morning. Jordan caught 4 fish and Perry caught double what Jordan caught. On the way back to shore, the boat tipped over and they lost one-fourth of their total catch. How many fish remain?<n>Output: Since Perry caught double what Jordan caught, Perry caught 2 * 4 = <<2*4=8>>8 fish.<n>Altogether, they caught 8 + 4 = <<8+4=12>>12 fish.<n>On the way back to the shore, they lost 12 * 1/4 = <<12*1/4=3>>3 fish.<n>They have 12 - 3 = <<12-3=9>>9 fish remaining.<n>So the final answer is 9<n><n>Input:What prevents someone from getting sleep at night? Choices:  A: relax B: dreams C: have nightmares D: restlessness E: snore<n>Output:		The answer is F, none. The only logical choice is none.<n>

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90. If the number of Doberman puppies is 20, how many Schnauzers are there?<n>Output: Three times the number of Doberman puppies is 3*20=<<3*20=60>>60<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies is 60-5=<<60-5=55>>55<n>Let's say the number of Schnauzers is s.<n>The difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is s-20<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90, meaning 55+s-20=90.<n>The number of Schnauzers which is s+55-20=90<n>This evaluates to s+35=90<n>There are s=<<55=55>>55 Schnauzers<n>So the final answer is 55<n><n>Input: Dr. Banks had 330 toothbrushes to give away to his patients. He gave away 53 toothbrushes in January. He gave away 67 toothbrushes in February. In March he gave away 46 toothbrushes. In April and May, he gave away the remaining toothbrushes, half each month.  How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Output: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>So the final answer is 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. On Tuesday, she picks half as many seashells as she did on Monday. Jordan caught 4 fish and Perry caught double what Jordan caught. On the way back to shore, the boat tipped over and they lost one-fourth of their total catch. How many fish remain?<n>Output: Since Perry caught double what Jordan caught, Perry caught 2 * 4 = <<2*4=8>>8 fish.<n>Altogether, they caught 8 + 4 = <<8+4=12>>12 fish.<n>On the way back to the shore, they lost 12 * 1/4 = <<12*1/4=3>>3 fish.<n>They have 12 - 3 = <<12-3=9>>9 fish remaining.<n>So the final answer is 9<n><n>Input:What do people look for when competing against someone? If each of her grandchildren had twice as many grandchildren as Amy does, will Amy be the youngest child in her family? Answer: Amy will NOT be the youngest child.<n>Output: Let there be a total of n children in Amy's family. <n><n>If each grandchild had twice as many grandkids as Amy does, the number of Amy's grandchildren would be 2n. <n><n>Now let's say Amy has N grandkids. If 2n is more than N, then this means that Amy is NOT the youngest child: 2 * N > N, so 2N > N, which means we can divide by 2 to get N > N / 2.<n><n>Answer: Amy will NOT be youngest family.<n><n>Input:You have a box which can hold a certain number of items. E is the only choice where the difference between the first two statements and the third two statements is more than the difference between the second two statements. (see details further down)<n>(A: -2 + 1 = -3, B: 3 + 2 = 5)<n>(E: -1 + 2 = 3, C: 1 + 1 = 2 not sufficient)<n>So the answer is 3<n><n>Input: What is the sum of all positive integers after 46?<n><n>Output: The sum of all postive numbers after 46 = 1 + 2 + 3 +... + 46 = 46 * (2/1) = 46 * 2 = 92<n><n>Input:What is the result of adding every digit one more time? (excluding the number of 9's)<n><n>Output: Since 11111 + 1 + 1 +... + 1 = 1111(1 + 1 +...+1)<n>It is an infinite number of digits.<n>Sorry, that's the correct answer.
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90. If the number of Doberman puppies is 20, how many Schnauzers are there?<n>Output: Three times the number of Doberman puppies is 3*20=<<3*20=60>>60<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies is 60-5=<<60-5=55>>55<n>Let's say the number of Schnauzers is s.<n>The difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is s-20<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90, meaning 55+s-20=90.<n>The number of Schnauzers which is s+55-20=90<n>This evaluates to s+35=90<n>There are s=<<55=55>>55 Schnauzers<n>So the final answer is 55<n><n>Input: Dr. Banks had 330 toothbrushes to give away to his patients. He gave away 53 toothbrushes in January. He gave away 67 toothbrushes in February. In March he gave away 46 toothbrushes. In April and May, he gave away the remaining toothbrushes, half each month.  How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Output: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>So the final answer is 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. On Tuesday, she picks half as many seashells as she did on Monday. If she can sell each seashell for $1.20, how much money can she make if she sells all of her seashells?<n>Output: On Tuesday, Sally picks 30 / 2 = <<30/2=15>>15 seashells<n>In total, Sally picks 30 + 15 = <<30+15=45>>45 seashells<n>The total amount of money Sally can make is 45 * $1.20 = $<<45*1.2=54>>54<n>So the final answer is 54<n><n>Input: Jordan and Perry took a boat out to the lake to go fishing on a Monday morning. Jordan caught 4 fish and Perry caught double what Jordan caught. On the way back to shore, the boat tipped over and they lost one-fourth of their total catch. How many fish remain?<n>Output: Since Perry caught double what Jordan caught, Perry caught 2 * 4 = <<2*4=8>>8 fish.<n>Altogether, they caught 8 + 4 = <<8+4=12>>12 fish.<n>On the way back to the shore, they lost 12 * 1/4 = <<12*1/4=3>>3 fish.<n>They have 12 - 3 = <<12-3=9>>9 fish remaining.<n>So the final answer is 9<n><n>Input:The keys were black and white, what were they attached to? Choices:  A: front pocket B: cabinet C: purse D: chain E: piano<n>Output:		Choice D: The keys were attached to the purse<n><n>Input: A dog is playing in the park and runs around the statue 4 times. Then he plays in the field where he starts a distance D miles away. After he plays in the field, he runs back to the park, starting from the exact same place he started from before he went to the field. How many whole miles did the dog run?<n>Output: He was 4 whole miles away from the starting point when he ran to the statue.<n>He ran around the statue 1 time, and it's not mentioned if it's whole or fractional.<n>Since he ran around the statue 4 whole times, the times he ran around the statue were: 1, 2, 3, and 4<n>To run "back" to the park, he actually traveled counterclockwise.<n>We assume he was one-half the distance away (D/2)<n>So, the distance he runs after running around the statue is<n>(D/2 - 1)/2 + 1 = <<D/2-1/2+1=3/2>>3/2 miles<n><n>If he is 3/2 miles away from the statute, it takes 1 whole mile to get back to the starting point.<n>We can say the 1 whole mile is a "time" of running around the statue.<n>In this case, it's 2 "times" around since it took him 2 whole miles to run to the starting point<n>This means if he ran around 3 times, he'd be 2/3 of the distance he started from.<n>We assume he ran around 3 "times" on the way back.<n>From the starting point, he went 1 mile to the field at (D/2) miles away.<n>The starting point is also 1 "time" of running, since he took 1 whole mile to go there.<n>This means the dog must have run a total of 4 times after he ran to the field.<n>He ran 1 mile when going from the starting point to the field, and 3 times more on the way back<n>The whole distance he ran is<n>((1 mile of travel to the field) + 3 "times" of running on the way to the field)<n>If he ran the whole 4 miles, he'd have to run 3 "times
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90. He gave away 53 toothbrushes in January. He gave away 67 toothbrushes in February. In March he gave away 46 toothbrushes. In April and May, he gave away the remaining toothbrushes, half each month.  How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Output: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>So the final answer is 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90. If the number of Doberman puppies is 20, how many Schnauzers are there?<n>Output: Three times the number of Doberman puppies is 3*20=<<3*20=60>>60<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies is 60-5=<<60-5=55>>55<n>Let's say the number of Schnauzers is s.<n>The difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is s-20<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90, meaning 55+s-20=90.<n>The number of Schnauzers which is s+55-20=90<n>This evaluates to s+35=90<n>There are s=<<55=55>>55 Schnauzers<n>So the final answer is 55<n><n>Input: Dr. Banks had 330 toothbrushes to give away to his patients. He gave away 53 toothbrushes in January. He gave away 67 toothbrushes in February. In March he gave away 46 toothbrushes. In April and May, he gave away the remaining toothbrushes, half each month.  How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Output: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>So the final answer is 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. On Tuesday, she picks half as many seashells as she did on Monday. If she can sell each seashell for $1.20, how much money can she make if she sells all of her seashells?<n>Output: On Tuesday, Sally picks 30 / 2 = <<30/2=15>>15 seashells<n>In total, Sally picks 30 + 15 = <<30+15=45>>45 seashells<n>The total amount of money Sally can make is 45 * $1.20 = $<<45*1.2=54>>54<n>So the final answer is 54<n><n>Input: Jordan and Perry took a boat out to the lake to go fishing on a Monday morning. Jordan caught 4 fish and Perry caught double what Jordan caught. On the way back to shore, the boat tipped over and they lost one-fourth of their total catch. How many fish remain?<n>Output: Since Perry caught double what Jordan caught, Perry caught 2 * 4 = <<2*4=8>>8 fish.<n>Altogether, they caught 8 + 4 = <<8+4=12>>12 fish.<n>On the way back to the shore, they lost 12 * 1/4 = <<12*1/4=3>>3 fish.<n>They have 12 - 3 = <<12-3=9>>9 fish remaining.<n>So the final answer is 9<n><n>Input:The window across the street was broken and John felt guilty. He never meant to damage what? How many fish remain?<n>Output: Since Perry caught double what Jordan caught, Perry caught 2 * 4 = <<2*4=8>>8 fish.<n>Altogether, they caught 8 + 4 = <<8+4=12>>12 fish.<n>On the way back to the shore, they lost 12 * 1/4 = <<12*1/4=3>>3 fish.<n>They have 12 - 3 = <<12-3=9>>9 fish remaining.<n>So the final answer is 9<n><n>Input:Where would you hear a viola along side many other string and brass instruments? Choices:  A: symphony B: band C: create music D: orchestra E: string quartet<n>Output:		Viola is both the second largest string instrument, and is the second least popular, making E the correct answer<n><n>Input:What are two words in English that almost always start with v?<n><n>Output: vase and vacuum<n><n>Input:If the value of the expression “1 + 2 + 3 + +2013” is 86,320, what other value, if any, could the expression evaluate to?<n><n>Output: 86320
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90. If the number of Doberman puppies is 20, how many Schnauzers are there?<n>Output: Three times the number of Doberman puppies is 3*20=<<3*20=60>>60<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies is 60-5=<<60-5=55>>55<n>Let's say the number of Schnauzers is s.<n>The difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is s-20<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90, meaning 55+s-20=90.<n>The number of Schnauzers which is s+55-20=90<n>This evaluates to s+35=90<n>There are s=<<55=55>>55 Schnauzers<n>So the final answer is 55<n><n>Input: Dr. Banks had 330 toothbrushes to give away to his patients. He gave away 53 toothbrushes in January. He gave away 67 toothbrushes in February. In March he gave away 46 toothbrushes. In April and May, he gave away the remaining toothbrushes, half each month.  How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Output: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>So the final answer is 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. On Tuesday, she picks half as many seashells as she did on Monday. If she can sell each seashell for $1.20, how much money can she make if she sells all of her seashells?<n>Output: On Tuesday, Sally picks 30 / 2 = <<30/2=15>>15 seashells<n>In total, Sally picks 30 + 15 = <<30+15=45>>45 seashells<n>The total amount of money Sally can make is 45 * $1.20 = $<<45*1.2=54>>54<n>So the final answer is 54<n><n>Input: Jordan and Perry took a boat out to the lake to go fishing on a Monday morning. Jordan caught 4 fish and Perry caught double what Jordan caught. On the way back to shore, the boat tipped over and they lost one-fourth of their total catch. How many fish remain?<n>Output: Since Perry caught double what Jordan caught, Perry caught 2 * 4 = <<2*4=8>>8 fish.<n>Altogether, they caught 8 + 4 = <<8+4=12>>12 fish.<n>On the way back to the shore, they lost 12 * 1/4 = <<12*1/4=3>>3 fish.<n>They have 12 - 3 = <<12-3=9>>9 fish remaining.<n>So the final answer is 9<n><n>Input:Where are small grapes used? ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90. How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Output: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>So the final answer is 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90. If the number of Doberman puppies is 20, how many Schnauzers are there?<n>Output: Three times the number of Doberman puppies is 3*20=<<3*20=60>>60<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies is 60-5=<<60-5=55>>55<n>Let's say the number of Schnauzers is s.<n>The difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is s-20<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90, meaning 55+s-20=90.<n>The number of Schnauzers which is s+55-20=90<n>This evaluates to s+35=90<n>There are s=<<55=55>>55 Schnauzers<n>So the final answer is 55<n><n>Input: Dr. Banks had 330 toothbrushes to give away to his patients. How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Output: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>So the final answer is 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. Jordan caught 4 fish and Perry caught double what Jordan caught. On the way back to shore, the boat tipped over and they lost one-fourth of their total catch. How many fish remain?<n>Output: Since Perry caught double what Jordan caught, Perry caught 2 * 4 = <<2*4=8>>8 fish.<n>Altogether, they caught 8 + 4 = <<8+4=12>>12 fish.<n>On the way back to the shore, they lost 12 * 1/4 = <<12*1/4=3>>3 fish.<n>They have 12 - 3 = <<12-3=9>>9 fish remaining.<n>So the final answer is 9<n><n>Input:A person is putting on makeup, what is their likely goal? Choices that are not true are not likely options.<n><n>Input: Either Alex picks M&Ms or picks the red M&Ms. Neither A: he will choose M&Ms B: he will choose red M&Ms C: he will be unsatisfied with any M&Ms he chooses D: he will be unsure about choosing M&Ms E: he will not eat any M&Ms<n>Output: A person will not be unsure about choosing the M&Ms, as that would mean they chose more than one M&M. ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90. If the number of Doberman puppies is 20, how many Schnauzers are there?<n>Output: Three times the number of Doberman puppies is 3*20=<<3*20=60>>60<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies is 60-5=<<60-5=55>>55<n>Let's say the number of Schnauzers is s.<n>The difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is s-20<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90, meaning 55+s-20=90.<n>The number of Schnauzers which is s+55-20=90<n>This evaluates to s+35=90<n>There are s=<<55=55>>55 Schnauzers<n>So the final answer is 55<n><n>Input: Dr. Banks had 330 toothbrushes to give away to his patients. He gave away 53 toothbrushes in January. He gave away 67 toothbrushes in February. In March he gave away 46 toothbrushes. In April and May, he gave away the remaining toothbrushes, half each month.  How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Output: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>So the final answer is 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. On Tuesday, she picks half as many seashells as she did on Monday.
